Class ResponseManager<R extends ResponseManager.Response<F>,F extends DynamicFormManager.DynamicForm>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.ac.ed.epcc.webapp.model.data.DataObjectFactory<R>
      • uk.ac.ed.epcc.webapp.model.far.response.ResponseManager<R,F>
  • Type Parameters:
    R - type of ResponseManager.Response
    F - type of DynamicFormManager.DynamicForm
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Contexed, ContextCached, FormCreatorProducer, FormUpdateProducer<R>, FilterMatcher<R>, TypeConverter<R,java.lang.Number>, Selector<DataObjectItemInput<R>>, Owner, IndexedProducer<R>, ServeDataProducer, Tagged, Targetted<R>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    PersonalResponseManager

    public abstract class ResponseManager<R extends ResponseManager.Response<F>,F extends DynamicFormManager.DynamicForm>
extends DataObjectFactory<R>
implements ServeDataProducer
    a factory for responses to DynamicFormManager.DynamicForms. This class is abstract because much of the behaviour (specifically how responses are created and the rules for who can edit a response) are very specific to the surrounding logic. ResponseManagers implement ServeDataProducer allowing any user

                               java.util.List<java.lang.String> path)

        Description copied from interface: ServeDataProducer
        get a download file-name to be added to a download link. This should be the same as the value returned by MimeStreamData.getName() if ServeDataProducer.getData(SessionService, List) returns a non-null value. However this method may be called by display content generation code so if the result is generated on the fly it might be possible to generate the download name in a more lightweight fashion. It should also work to always return null thought he browser will use the last part of the selection path as the download
